  "prompt": "Why wasn't John Williams hired to write the soundtrack to Rogue One?",
  "response": "John Williams was not hired to write the soundtrack for *Rogue One: A Star Wars Story* primarily due to scheduling conflicts.\n\nHere's the breakdown:\n\n*   **Tight Timeline:** *Rogue One* was a standalone film that came out relatively quickly after Disney acquired Lucasfilm. This meant a compressed production schedule. John Williams, at the time, was already committed to composing the score for *Star Wars: The Force Awakens* which was the return to the core Star Wars films. This would have conflicted with the timeline for *Rogue One*.\n\n*   **Williams's Primary Focus:** John Williams has always prioritized composing for the main saga films. With his involvement in *The Force Awakens* and subsequent episodes, his schedule simply didn't allow him to take on the additional commitment of scoring a standalone film like *Rogue One*.\n\n*   **Giacchino's Availability:** Michael Giacchino, a highly respected and accomplished composer in his own right, was available and willing to step in. Giacchino had previously worked with Lucasfilm on video game scores, making him a familiar choice.\n\nUltimately, it was a matter of John Williams being unable to commit to *Rogue One* due to his prior obligations to the main saga films and the film's production timeline. Michael Giacchino's availability made him a fitting replacement.",
